******
[2] Date: Thu 12 Jul 2007
Source: The Courier-Mail [edited]
<http://www.news.com.au/couriermail/story/0,23739,22060459-3102,00.html>

Cane smut has been found in north Queensland's Burdekin and further
south in Maryborough, meaning the disease has spread almost the full
length of the state's major cane growing areas. It confirms fears the
entire 500 000 hectare [about 1.24 million acres] crop might have to
be ploughed out. Cane growers chief executive, Ian Ballantyne,
yesterday [11 Jul 2007] predicted reduced production levels and the
planting of replacement crops would cost hundreds of million of
dollars.
Bureau of Sugar Experiment Stations [BSES] program leader, Mike Cox,
said the outbreak was now widespread. BSES had sufficient disease
resistant material ready for any farmer to replant, he said.
[Byline: Brian Williams]
--
Communicated by:
J. Allan Dodds
Former ProMED-mail plant disease moderator
<dodds@ucr.edu>
[Sugarcane smut is caused by the fungus _Sporisorium scitamineum_. It
is highly infectious and can be spread by wind or carried on clothing
and machinery. Symptoms are a black whip-like structure emerging from
the central core of meristematic tissues, which contains the spores.
Disease management includes use of resistant cultivars and burning of
infected fields after harvest. Sugarcane smut appears to be present
in every sugarcane-growing country worldwide. More information on the
disease can be found in the recent ProMED-mail post 20070604.1800.
